A really good turn-based puzzle game. It's amazing how cleverly it adapts the source material, and the commitment to the Board Game motif is charming. New mechanics are added slowly over time as the player moves Agent 47 around urban locations; building up to the assassinations which throw complicated patterns while Ave Maria plays. Some later puzzles do get complicated and there are only a few mechanics to spice up the puzzles in between, so it's not perfect. But it's fun for what it is.

Hitman Go is the kind of game that, if not for the mobile space, you would only see on the NES or ancient PC's. It is a game that takes the core mechanics of the Hitman games- stealth, dodging guards, assassinations, and disguises- and distills them into their purest, most abstract form. Adding to its old school appeal is the fact that there's no story, no tutorial, no text whatsoever! Plus, the board game aesthetic is super creative, and really adds to the feeling of the game being a miniaturized abstraction of Agent 47's assassin hijinks. Intuitive pick up and play controls and great puzzle design make this one of the best games on mobile.
Though it breaks the style of the Hitman franchise, the tone is conveyed very well

This is very different to the lara croft and deus ex go games. While they went with scifi, and cartoon level type graphics, this one instead opts for maximum graphical realism of the wholly artificial world on a series of game boards. The sound varies between scenes with hauntingly beautiful opera, and scenes with irritating sounds that get on your nerves with every frequent repetition. It does have a more mature feel, and the puzzles are a little trickier than either of the others. It seems like the sort of game that Michael Gove might play whilst smoking cigars and drinking brandy, and wishing he was as strong as all the big lads. Secretly plotting his rise to Prime minister while absent mindedly thumbing the pages of Macbeth.

I really can't reccomend this, even though I got it with google credit. The 
controls try so hard to be minimalistic, that one swipe of the screen can 
mean like 5 different things. Trying to move your piece by one space can 
make the camera zoom out, do a flip, and focus on the other half of the 
map. Additionally, instead of having large, interesting maps, every level 
is tiny with a huge number of dead-end options that make the level 
unwinnable in advance with no indication. It quickly becomes a game of 
simon says, and contradicts the whole "act well under pressure" idea that 
the original games are supposed to embody. The tutorial levels try to teach 
you that computer pieces move in a predictible way that you can exploit. 
But they don't. You never know when THIS PARTICULAR piece is going to do a 
180 when it gets to its destination. Another piece may decide to go PAST 
the sound it was following and walk on a new track for no apparent reason. 
In addition, in an effort to make up for the lack of larger levels, many 
levels have multiple conflicting objectives, meaning you'll have to do the 
same thing over and over again without learning anything new. All while 
fighting the controls which - as i said - are constantly bucking the camera 
across the map without your consent

This game is something special. Gameplay is fun and challenging, but the real attraction (for me, anyway) lies in the boardgame aesthetic that informs every aspect of the game, right down to that delightful click-rattle when you "ice" somebody by knocking their piece off the board. The tiny, fake environments appeal to my love of miniatures and models, and there is something sublime about taking the dark and bloody goings-on of Hitman and filtering it through the aggressively bright and cheerful lens of a family-friendly boardgame. I can't get enough of the concept, and I really wish they'd continued it in the later Go games. Some of the challenges can get irritating, but mostly, they were the right level of difficulty. I can't recommend this game enough and I kinda wish it could exist as a physical boardgame, though given the detailed sets, it would probably cost all the money...all of it.

I haven't yet finished it, but I am loving this game. The stylistic board game look really works, and it is surprisingly challenging. I also find the music is perfect for the game - in the background, but soothing without being muzak. It was a coincidence that I am playing the very first of the series last, but I can definitely see why it was a hit. This is an exceptionally well put together game period, never mind for mobile.   It may lack the fancy animations of the later games, but it makes up for it with a purist view of turn-based strategy puzzles. There is enough fluff to make it interesting, but not so much to distract from the goal. I would definitely recommend it if you like turn-based puzzles.

If you are deciding between this and Lara croft Go. Skip this game. While similar in concept, Lara Croft is beautifully stylized with full animation for all characters, as well as some dramatic elements thrown it.  Hitman go has great visuals but characters are animated as static gameboard type objects, it feels either like a knock off of that game or a prototype of it. It's saving grace is that it is more challenging and each level has multiple objectives. Each objective is somewhat optional, but some make the individual levels quite repetitive as you will find yourself doing each at least twice to get some of the objectives fulfilled.

The power to choose really plays out in this game and the puzzles are really challenging. The only thing I would have added to the game is more weapon choice. Keep in mind that when I am writing this review I am about 86% through the game. The sniper rifle is cool and the pistols are a fun edition when you need them but they very rarely show up and considering the amount of when enemies you have to combat I really would have loved to have a close range feature like a knife or a bat perhaps. It also would have been cool to see some defence items as well. But hey there are always sequel:) overall a really fun and entertaining game and I am currently still trying to find a better GO videogame out there.

A deceptively challenging puzzle game with nice graphics and sound.  In this game, you move your token (hit-man) around the board (room), one square at a time along a dotted path. The objective is to make it to the exit, on the way traversing a predetermined spot on the board (i.e. executing the hit on your target), and sometimes pick up a briefcase lying somewhere in the room.  In the course of completing your assignment, you bump other tokens (fellow villains) off the board, or simply give them a wide berth. You can pick up and throw objects to influence the movement of the other tokens and hide behind a plant to make yourself temporarily invisible  If you strip away the slick audiovisuals, the game could actually be represented by ASCII characters on a VT100 terminal. The core of the game is really its mechanics; the rest is just pretty fluff.  Nevertheless, the professional look of the game does make it more fun to play, and enough levels are included to make the game more than a wet afternoon's worth.  The game certainly isn't cheap given its relatively simple core concept, but if you can get it on 80% discount as I did, it's worth the reduced price of admission.

I picked up Hitman GO after hearing good things about Lara Croft GO and Deus Ex GO. At a very reasonable ¬£1.34 after my Google Play subscription discount, I downloaded the game intending to play a level or two and come back to it later. I was immediately hooked by the quirky and unique art style, funny but subtle NPC sounds, and varied game mechanics.  The game is beautifully animated and each level has a number of different objectives to achieve in order to 100% them - kill all targets before completing, kill no targets and complete, collect an item before escaping, complete in >x turns etc. So far I've 100%'d the first 12 or so levels and absolutely love the game.  Generally speaking, I find turn-based or non-time-sensitive games to be perfect for mobile gaming where precise aim/twitch reactions aren't always possible, and this game fits that bill perfectly. I can definitely see myself picking up Lara Croft GO and Deus Ex GO on completing this one. Well done Squeenix!

This is a puzzle game. That is something you need to understand before you pick this up. It's themed on the Hitman franchise, but there's no violence or gore. The gameplay is very simple, you get a turn.. the computer gets a turn, rinse and repeat. During your turn you move Agent 47 by sliding him across a line/grid in order to either just move, kill someone by approaching them from any direction but the front or pick up/use an item. Sometimes you'll find something to throw to distract the guards in order to move them away from their guard spots or routes. And that's really all there's to it. It's one of those puzzle games that's really simple to grasp, but which gets harder to farther you go.  And IMO there's no game that's not worth $0.99 Just don't go into this thinking it's a classical Hitman game, you can remove Agent 47 from the game and you'd still have a fun little puzzle game.

This game is well worth your time. The puzzles are pretty finely tuned, giving you a mix of relatively simple ones, intermediate challenges, and really tough conundrums. While adjacent levels offer varying degrees of challenge, the difficulty curve as a whole is good, carefully introducing new mechanics throughout. Each level has bonus objectives, giving the levels meaningful replay value and additional difficulty. One of the game's strong suits is its presentation. For a mobile game, it's quite gorgeous. Finally, the game is surprisingly well designed to keep the feel of a Hitman game, and does it very well. It feels like a Hitman game despite being a mobile puzzler. It's not entirely perfect, though. Although it has a nice difficulty curve, some players may find that the puzzles offer few surprises and curveballs, and it may feel a bit samey throughout. There are some tiny niggles in the UI, as well. The most prominent example might be that zooming out, while possible, is fickle and difficult, resulting in a claustrophobic feel. In summary, it's a very good, cheap piece of game design that will offer hours of fun. Highly recommended.

Some other reviewers dismiss the game play as simple and gherefore unchallenging. It is simple: motion is turn-based and constrained.  Overlaid on the beautiful dioramas is a map; the map consists of locations and lines connecting those locations (in mathematical terms, a graph).  On each turn you must move exactly one location in the map.  Your assailants move in their turns.  When you move you may die immediately, you may trap yourself in future death, or you may keep your chances alive...

The board game format is a vastly different experience for the franchise. However, GO still feels distinctly Hitman. All the strategy, planning, and execution are there; you must think about how you maneuver around the various patrols and marks as you would in any Hitman game. Square Enix even fit in throwable distractions, hiding places, and yes, disguises. Overall, GO is a very smooth and challenging puzzle game that will please both Hitman fans and puzzlephiliacs who have never played a Hitman game.

This game is NOT a traditional Hitman game. It's a puzzle game in the style of a board game. You move Agent 47 along specific paths. Along those paths are enemies and items. This won't scratch your itch if you're looking for something like the main hitman games, but is great fun if you want a puzzle game set in the Hitman universe.

To be sure this game would work if presented in a flat, two-dimensional format.  But the understated yet ultra-cool 3D graphic design serves to catapult Hitman GO into the stratosphere of the elite. Never before has one seen a board, puzzle, or strategy game so executed and the result is a product that is as visually arresting to the eyes as it is challenging to the mind.  As a fan of the old Windows based Professor Fizzwizzle strategy puzzle game I had lamented the lack of something similar for the Android platform.  This app has satisfied my jones for intelligent gameplay.  Loaded aboard my Samsung Galaxy Tab Pro 12.2 the game screams sophistication so loudly the super hot woman sitting beside me commented on it. Well worth a $5 bill.
